REMARKS: ID BY SMITHSONIAN. FLT CREW ADVISED SEEING A FLOCK OF BIRDS (10-12) AT 4300 FT, 13-15 MILES FROM RWY 30L. 2 HIT THE A/C. ONE AT #1 ENG COWLING, THE OTHER ON L WING LE SLATS. COLLECTED WHITE FEATHER AND SNARGE SAMPLE OF WHAT APPEARS TO BE A TUNDRA SWAN. SAMPLE WILL BE SENT FOR ID. AIRLINE INFO INDICATED PILOTS SAW ABOUT A DOZEN LARGE, WHITE BIRDS AND HAD MULTIPLE AUDIBLE STRIKES. THEY NOTICED A SLIGHT CHANGE IN ENG INDICATIONS ON THE #1 ENG BUT THAT QUICKLY STABILIZED. WITHIN ABOUT 10 SECONDS THEY RECEIVED A SLAT FAIL CAUTION MESSAGE. PILOTS ASKED ATC TO MAINTAIN 4000' AND A VECTOR AWAY FROM THE APCH END TO RUN A CHECKLIST AND ADVISED THEM OF THE STRIKE. A/C LANDED W/O EVENT. DAMAGE WAS SIGNIFICANT TO BOTH IMPACT POINTS - #1 ENG NACELLE LEADING EDGE AND LH SLAT AT ABOUT THE WING'S MIDPOINT. (DATA ENTRY NOTE: ARPT DAILY LOG SHOWS STRIKE OCCURRED APPROX 7 MILE FINAL AT APPROX 3500' AGL. AIRCRAFT WENT AROUND BUT DID NOT DECLARE AN EMERGENCY.)
